    ```javascript
function minFlips(a, b, c) {
    let count = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
        let bitA = (a >> i) & 1;
        let bitB = (b >> i) & 1;
        let bitC = (c >> i) & 1;
        if (bitC === 0) {
            count += bitA + bitB;
        } else {
            count += 1 - (bitA | bitB);
        }
    }
    return count;
}
```

    We iterate through all 32 bits since the maximum number is 10^9, which requires 30 bits to represent in binary. For each bit, we determine the bits for `a`, `b`, and `c`, at the current position. If the bit in `c` is 0, we increment the counter by the sum of the bits of `a` and `b` at that position. This is because we need to flip any 1s in `a` and `b` to make the OR result 0. If the bit in `c` is 1, we increment the counter by 1 minus the OR result of `a` and `b`. This is because either `a` or `b` (or both) need to have a 1 at this position, so 1 minus the OR result gives us the necessary flips.

